Title: Synthesis of a high-resolution 3D-stereoscopic image pair from a high-resolution monoscopic image and a low-resolution
Author: Kyung-tae Kim a,* Mel Siegel a Jung-Young Son b 
Keyword: stereoscopy, stereo cameras, 3D-TV, disparity, occlusion, view interpolation  
Address: Pittsburgh PA 15213  Korea  
Affiliation: a The Robotics Institute School of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University,  b Korea Institute of Science and Technology (KIST), Seoul,  
Abstract: We describe a new low-level scheme to achieve high definition 3D-stereoscopy within the bandwidth of the monoscopic HDTV infrastructure. Our method uses a studio quality monoscopic high resolution color camera to generate a transmitted main stream view, and a anking 3D-stereoscopic pair of low cost, low resolution monochrome camera outriggers to generate a depth map of the scene. The depth map is deeply compressed and transmitted as a low bandwidth auxiliary stream. The two streams are recombined at the receiver to generate a 3D-stereoscopic pair of high resolution color views from the perspectives of the original outriggers. Alternatively, views from two arbitrary perspectives between (and, to a limited extent, beyond) the low resolution monoscopic camera positions can be synthesized to accommodate individual viewer preferences. We describe our algorithms, and the design and outcome of initial experiments. The experiments begin with three NTSC color images, degrade the outer pair to low resolution monochrome, and compare the results of coding and reconstruction to the originals. 
